        <details>
          <summary>Abstract</summary>
          <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Absence of substantial investment in the development of human
            resources in developing
            countries as evidenced in Nigeria led to ebb of economy as a result of inadequate human
            development, mismanagement and misuse of resources. Earlier studies in Nigeria focused on
            human resource development and economic growth/ investment in human capital with no
            intense emphasis linked to economic development in the literature. This study examined the
            inter-relationship between human resources and economic development in Nigeria using
            annual time series data spans between 1981 and 2018. Data for the study were sourced from
            the United Nation Development Programme (UNDP) and World Bank, World Development
            Indicator (WDI) database. The data for the study was analyze using Vector Auto-regression
            (VAR) as estimation technique. Result from the study showed that life expectancy rate (LEXR),
            labour force (LABF) and population growth rate (POPgr) contributes greatly (43%, 37% and
            33% respectively) to economic development in Nigeria than literacy rate (LITR) having low
            proportion of 4% influence. Further, the result of impulse response (IRFs) analysis showed that
            LEXR and LABF impacted positively to economic development in the country during the study
            period. Based on these findings, it is recommended that the influence of human resources on
            economic development is indispensable taken into consideration some variables like life
            expectancy rate, labour force and population growth rate, particularly when government and
            policymakers are considering economic policy in the country.</article>
        </details>
