        <hr>
        <details>
          <summary>Abstract</summary>
          <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> One of the major factors affecting the growth of manufacturing output
            is the unstable
            macroeconomics variables such as money supply and inflation. Thus, this study examined the
            dynamics of money supply, inflation and manufacturing output in Nigeria. Secondary data on
            Money Supply, Inflation and Manufacturing Output from 1986 to 2018 were obtained from
            Centre Bank of Nigeria and World Development Indicators. The study carried out necessary
            diagnostic test such as; Unit root test, Normality test, Breusch-Godfrey LM test and Johansen
            Cointegration test. The unit root test indicated that all variables were stationary at first
            difference. While, the cointegration test indicated the adopted variables were cointegrated. The
            normality test indicated that some variables were normally distributed and the Breusch-Godfrey
            LM indicated that the variables were not serially correlated. The result of the Error Correction
            Model revealed that the error correction term (ect) was 0.365 and correctly signed. This means
            that the disequilibrium in the model was corrected at 36.5% in the long run. The Error
            Correction model also showed that money supply, exchange rate and inflation have negative
            effect on manufacturing output. Finally, the Pairwise Granger causality test showed that
            unidirectional causality relationship existed from money supply to manufacturing output and
            manufacturing output to exchange rate. Based on these findings, the study concluded that
            money supply, exchange rate and inflation negatively affect manufacturing output activities is
            Nigeria. Similarly, money supply affects manufacturing output activities and manufacturing
            output triggers the exchange rate. The study recommended that government should formulate
            policies that will ensure exchange rate stability in order to enables prediction of the cost of
            imported needed materials or inputs in relation to manufacturing activities, because of the
            negative effect of money supply and inflation on manufacturing output, policies that would
            reduce these effect should be encouraged by the monetary authority in Nigeria.</article>
        </details>
